                                     <dimensions unit="m">
                                            <height>1.95</height>
                                            <width>0.20</width>
                                            <depth>0.15</depth>                                   
                                    </dimensions>                            
                                </support>
                                <condition>The stone is quite weathered and spalled. Although not included by Macalister in his 1945 Corpus, Westropp (1914, 77) recorded this stone as showing <q>notches on the natural-squared edge and faint traces of straight and slant scores</q></condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>Traces of a possible ogham inscription (presumably reading upwards) can be seen on the north-west angle of the pillar.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The strokes near the ground are slanted and probably <rs type="execution"  key="pocked" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">pocked</rs> but only evident on the B side (<foreign xml:lang="ga">Aicme Beithe</foreign>) of the angle.
                                <height/><!--letter-heights-->
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                             <origPlace corresp="#findspot">
                                 <placeName type="site">Cross Abbey (<foreign xml:lang="ga"><ref target="https://www.logainm.ie/ga/1399343">Mainistir na Croise</ref></foreign>)</placeName>, 
                                 <placeName type="townland">Cross (Boyd) (<foreign xml:lang="ga">An Chrois</foreign>)</placeName>, <placeName type="county">Co. Mayo</placeName>
                                <geo>54.208993, -10.083446</geo>
                             <note>ITM Coordinates: 464096, 830903</note></origPlace>
                            <origDate/>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance type="found" notAfter="1914"><persName><surname>Westropp</surname></persName> (1914, 77) recorded this stone as one of two tall stone pillars, one on either side of a <q>walled burial space, 7 feet wide [2.1m], which spanned the width of the church... on the E side of the burial space at Cross Abbey</q>, which was possibly an early Christian church site (<ref target="https://monasticon.celt.dias.ie/2930">Monasticon Hibernicum</ref>).
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed" when="2022">The ogham stone is incorporated into the outer edge of the low E wall of the grave structure, at a distance of 1.1m from the N wall of the church. The base of the stone is flanked on the S, W and N sides by the grave wall; the E face is more or less flush with the external face of the grave wall (Archaeological Survey of Ireland, Field Report). 3d recorded as part of the Mayo Ogham project <date>2022</date>, funded by The Heritage Council and Mayo County Council.
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
